passages.name: dreaming
passages.text:
You remember a place where this was held necessary: that she who ruled them must be mad.

When the old queen died, therefore, the news was kept from her successor. Instead, all would be just as before, save that those who served her would shrink from her touch, and what she said they would act if as if they did not hear. Yet if she would repeat it they would answer without memory of what she had first spoken, and if she made reference to something that had come before, they would say that they did not know, and ask if she were dreaming.

On the second day one will come who says that she is her sister, and greet her with great warmth and kindness, and ask why she does not know her, for are they not of one flesh? And she will tell the new queen of all their youth together, and ask why she does not remember.

[[From the third day she shall be fed nothing but black flowers.]]

passages.name: setupFights
passages.text:
<<set $fight = {
getRival: function(who){
	if ($gregTools.includesCreature($myCreatures,who)) {$enemyTeam = $AICreatures}
	else {$enemyTeam = $myCreatures};
	return this.findOccupier($enemyTeam,who.location);
},
findOccupier: function(list,where){
	for (var item in list) {
		if (list[item].location == where) {return list[item]}
	};
	return null
},
conduct: function(who){
	var rival = this.getRival(who);
	var battleData = who.battle[rival.name];
	if (battleData.dies == "me") {this.kill(who)}
	else if (battleData.dies == "them") {this.kill(rival)}
	else if (battleData.dies == "both") {this.kill(who);this.kill(rival)}
	else if (battleData.dies == "neither") {}
},
show: function(who){
	return who.battle[this.getRival(who).name].text + "\sn"
},
kill: function(who){
	if ($gregTools.includesCreature($AICreatures,who)) {
		$AICreatures.splice($gregTools.indexOfCreature($AICreatures,who),1)
	}
	else {
		$myCreatures.splice($gregTools.indexOfCreature($myCreatures,who),1)
	}
},
}>>

passages.name: WrathEffect
passages.text:
A sense of weight fills the space before you, hovers a second, then lifts and is gone.

The ground before you stands empty. Of the life and spirit that once made it a battlefield, of the heroes and monsters who fought there, the bare blank earth is all that remains.

[[Your rival raises an impressed eyebrow, and does not speak.|Main]]<<set $myCreatures = []>><<set $AICreatures = []>><<set $myHand.splice($myHand.indexOf('Wrath'),1)>>

passages.name: hesitate
passages.text:
You remember a place where this was held necessary: that she who ruled them must be mad.

When the rules of the world were changed, therefore, the news was kept from those whom it concerned. Instead, all would be just as before, save that those who had once obeyed would come forward as enemies, and what was said they would act if as if they did not hear. Yet all that was repeated they would answer, for they knew, they remembered all that had happened, and would ask if she were dreaming.

On the second day one will come who says that she is our sister, and greet us with great warmth and kindness, and ask why we do not know her, for are we not both purged of our flesh? And she will ask of our youth together, of sacrifices, agonies in a bare white cell, and ask why we do not remember.

From the third day we shall be fed nothing at all.

On the fourth day we shall find in our chamber knives, curved and sharp in every secret place, in every drawer and every closet, under the pillows and between the pages of books, and when we peer into mirrors we shall see only knives. And if we ask them removed we shall be told only that there are knives, too, underneath our skin, knives behind our eyes. For after all, did we not enjoy the thought of such dedication? And those who love us will come, and point to our flesh, and tell us that no-one who was worthy would hesitate.

On the fifth day all those come to us will do so purified of skin, cleansed of all weakness. And at all we tell them they will laugh, and spit out blood, and ask by what right we can possibly command. And once more they will gesture to the knife, and we will know exactly [[what to do.|what to do redux]]

[[Refuse.|Main]]

passages.name: Summon Avashi
passages.text:
To weave the flesh, they held, could not be learned of another. She who would do so, having entered first into seclusion, must let her own skin instruct her, must from every ragged scrap extract all that she could. When none remained, when the body had been honed to the red rawness of muscle and tendon beneath, then was her pupilage complete.

The one you remember had dwelt so long in her cell that though food was still brought it was assumed that she was dead, that she had taken from herself something too vital to continue. 

But she had merely been patient. Each tiny fleck of her torn body she had studied until she had learned its every secret and so could discard it without doubt or hesitation. And when she was ready, she had opened the door of her cell skinless and come forth.

You are remembering how, on the day she emerged, she stood ecstatic over the guards they had sent to find her, their broken bodies twisting in the air like rags, heartsblood jutting forwards and back, over and over, to the cruel metronome of her hands.

<<click "Focus on her memory." Action>> 
<<set $summoning to $avashi>>
<<display "Summoning">>
<</click>>

passages.name: Summon Golem
passages.text:
Of Zebu, who conquered half a continent without fighting a battle, you have no memory whatsoever.

Your master had seen to that. The same night that you'd returned, full of youthful enthusiasm for the wonders that you'd seen, he'd plucked away the memory like a ripe fig, taken it for his own - as was his right, as you'd known that he would. To thank you was not in his nature, but you could tell that he was impressed.

And you were rewarded. For he left you with your other memory of that silent, sudden conquest, that of the Herald. You had concealed nothing - it would, after all, have been quite futile to lie. Yet he'd left you still the image of that colossus, a thing of gleaming steel sixty feet high, which had proved through the terror of its presence such an effective negotiator. 

You remember the long, aching nights you'd passed, bound fast among the thick cables of its hair, deafened by the clamour of feet that never ceased to stride. You remember the way its fists had curled around some city official, his terms unsatisfactory, until he screamed, until he stopped. 

Yes, your master had been kind. 

<<click "Focus on this memory." Action>>

<<display "Summoning">>
<</click>>

passages.name: WrackEffect
passages.text:
<> Yet you can find no enemy here to touch with madness, no mind to turn and sculpt and guide to gibbering ruin.

[[Not yet.|Main]] <> <> You let madness ride with the band, watch as the eyes of your target widen. You have compressed the long days of the breaking well, and in seconds one among them is wild, shouting, grabbing at the others in panic and confusion.

For a moment, the riders seem to teeter between pity and contempt for such extravagent weakness. Then pragmatism carries the day, for strong arms hurl your victim to the ground, and hooves trample out the mind you'd shattered with such careful artistry.

And the band [[ride on|AICast]]. <> <> Your lips purse, then shudder and writhe. From inside your throat, you echo the rattle of chains, send something floating above that bitter and stagnant heat, sew ash and cinders in great invisible clouds upon the thing beneath.

They bloom like seeds. For the thing inside is half-mad already, and turns inwards, and you know that it whispers to itself of the long years of captivity, of escape, revenge. It goads and promises. It knows exactly what to say, the perfect screws to turn.

The heat shimmers once, twice, and is gone. On the ground beneath, a tiny silver mask, its features grotesquely twisted to an expression of perfect and matchless horror.

[[So.|AICast]]<> <> <> Staring upwards at that vast insectile crowd, you watch as a single form begins to buzz erratically, then fly away from the swarm entirely, pursued by a couple of others.

One might consider this an inefficient use of your [[talents|AICast]]. <> <> The palace attendants have gathered before Inai. She is young here, almost a child. They hold the skulls of rams. Their faces are riddles.

It seems for a moment grotesque - that you must expend so many, to bend the will of just one. But you must be sure. To calculate risk, to sacrifice no more or less than what is expendable - on this you have built success. This is what has always been required.

-

She laughs. The guards become music, vanish in a bright shower of sound. Attendants shimmer into mist. Into the sky drift tiny stars, small perfect hearts, miniature golden coins.

Back on the battlefield, Inai looks at you and [[smiles.|AICast]] <>

passages.name: PCGameOver
passages.text: <>No obstacle, no trick, now stands between Inai and your enemy. You know, as she closes the final few feet between them, that his mind is bare, that all he has seen you have faced down and overcome. She lifts up her dagger as he blinks concession. Your bonds drop off like wax. THE END<>Avashi stands before your rival. You know, as she closes the final few feet between them, that his mind is bare, that all he has seen you have faced down and overcome. Slowly, almost gently, she lifts her hand, and the ropes around him begin to tighten. You wait until the skin beneath is bruised and livid, until each breath is sharper than the last, until frantic eyes blink concession. Your bonds drip off like wax. {end}<>Your mind is bare. All day you have given to your rival the things you have seen, and each has been met and answered. And yet you are unconquered. You have not proved yourself, as you had wished. But you have survived. And surely there will be another time. {end}<>

passages.name: Summon Thalia
passages.text:
You are remembering how she turned, slowly, with patience, to a man twenty or thirty or forty years older, who was weeping.

It was the worst place in the world and the dead rose endlessly, hopelessly, their black arms clawing at life, and even those bodies that they burned came back as a sickness in the air. All day the long wait for help (but villages, towns, all around had fallen into blackness), and every night the dead hands beating at the palisade, and nothing to hope for but dawn.

She cannot even have been twenty - there must have been a time, not long before, when she had been too young to lead them.

Her dagger moves with her speech, and the sunset burns on its bright, cold steel. She is telling them that grief, too, is a luxury. That it must wait for victory; that until the night had passed they must be united in a single thought. Behind her, a band of twelve or fifteen, farmers mostly, their faces cold and sure.

Her name was Inai. It meant 'lucky', and was a lie.

<<click "Focus on her memory." Action>> 
<<set $summoning to $inai>>
<<display "Summoning">>
<</click>>
[[No, not yet.|Main]]

passages.name: A voice like a chorus.
passages.text: <<print "\s"You did not save them\s", she says. \s"My people. Not even one.\s"\n\sn\sn\nAnd it's true. You had your memory, your champion in her shining moment. And when she fell, there was nothing more to see. But wasn't that the point, after all? To abstract away each suffering particular, to be as ruthless, as relentlessly pragmatic as possible? [[You had your justifications.]]">>

includesCreature: function(list,creature) {
	for (var item in list) {
		if (list[item].name == creature.name) {return list[item]};
	};
	return false
},
indexOfCreature: function(list,creature) {
	for (var item in list) {
		if (list[item].name == creature.name) {return item};
	};
	return -1
},
preMoveVictoryCheck: function(teamName) {
	var whichTeam = $myCreatures;
	if (teamName == 'AI') {whichTeam = $AICreatures}
	
	for (var i in whichTeam) {
		if (whichTeam[i].location == 3 && teamName == "PC") {
			return whichTeam[i]
		}
		if (whichTeam[i].location == 1 && teamName == "AI") {
			return whichTeam[i]
		}
	};
	return false
},
PCCreatureAt: function(loc) {
	for (var i in $myCreatures) {
		if ($myCreatures[i].location == loc) {return true}
	}
	return false
},
}>>

passages.name: From the third day she shall be fed nothing but black flowers.
passages.text:
You remember a place where this was held necessary: that she who ruled them must be mad.

When the old queen died, therefore, the news was kept from her successor. Instead, all would be just as before, save that those who served her would shrink from her touch, and what she said they would act if as if they did not hear. Yet if she would repeat it they would answer without memory of what she had first spoken, and if she made reference to something that had come before, they would say that they did not know, and ask if she were dreaming.

On the second day one will come who says that she is her sister, and greet her with great warmth and kindness, and ask why she does not know her, for are they not of one flesh? And she will tell the new queen of all their youth together, and ask why she does not remember.

From the third day she shall be fed nothing but black flowers.

On the fourth day she shall find in her chamber knives, curved and sharp in every secret place, in every drawer and every closet, under the pillows and between the pages of books, and when she peers into mirrors she should see only knives, by trick of the glass. And if she asks them removed then servants will come with sacks heaped high with cinders, and say nothing but sow great handfuls of ash upon every surface. And if she asks why this is so, she shall be told only that there are knives, too, underneath her skin, [[knives behind her eyes.|wrackFullText]]

passages.name: wrackFullText
passages.text:
On the second day one will come who says that she is her sister, and greet her with great warmth and kindness, and ask why she does not know her, for are they not of one flesh? And she will tell the new queen of all their youth together, and ask why she does not remember.

From the third day she shall be fed nothing but black flowers.

On the fourth day she shall find in her chamber knives, curved and sharp in every secret place, in every drawer and every closet, under the pillows and between the pages of books, and when she peers into mirrors she should see only knives, by trick of the glass. And if she asks them removed then servants will come with sacks heaped high with cinders, and say nothing but sow great handfuls of ash upon every surface. And if she asks why this is so, she shall be told only that there are knives, too, underneath her skin, knives behind her eyes.

On the fifth day those who attend her will do so flecked with blood. And whatever she tells them first they will not hear, just as before, but whatever she tells them second they will laugh, and spit out blood, and answer in a language that she does not understand. 

By the sixth day it is expected she shall have made the order that all who serve her be put to death, and thus have proven that she is fit to rule. And if she does not, yet further measures may be employed. But this you did not see.

passages.text: For the first time, you allow yourself to notice your adversary. Strange to see him bound there, trussed as tightly as you are, the same black ropes pressing vivid against his skin. From sixty yards, all of your differences seem absurd, inconsequential.\n\nBut you were the one challenged. Custom dictates that you make [[the first move|Main]].

The rope is thin, black, thoroughly practical. Your hands wind through practised motions, lashing yourself fast to the stake behind. 

You pull the rope tight about your chest. Better to be sure.

passages.name: Cast Wrath
passages.text:
Somebody less experienced, someone without your talent, would have remembered the day that the valley had flooded. The grain of that stiff lever in the hands that pulled, and then the impossible speed of the rising waters, the panic of those (foolish stubborn old) who had chosen to remain. 

And extracted from this - an essence of what, exactly? The callousness of bureaucracies, perhaps. Something obscure and specific. 

But you needed something useful. So instead, you'll remember the day on which the waters began to recede, and you saw what lay beneath, or did not. The nothingness of houses smashed to shards of broken wood. The silence. The emptiness. The drowned bodies of the rats.

It's so much cleaner that way. 

[[Focus on this memory.|WrathEffect]]

<<set $AI = {
makeChoice: function(){


if ($myCreatures[0] && $myCreatures[0].name == "Golem" && $AICreatures.length == 0 && $AIHand.indexOf('Shatter') > -1 && $AIHand.indexOf('Prison') > 1) {return $AIHand.indexOf('Shatter')}

if ($AICreatures.length == 0) {
	var cNames = ['Raiders', 'Liespeaker','Locusts','Thing'];
	for (var cName in cNames) {
		if ($AIHand.indexOf(cNames[cName]) > -1) {
			return $AIHand.indexOf(cNames[cName])
		};
	};
};
	
if ($gregTools.PCCreatureAt(3) && $AIHand.indexOf('Prison') > -1 && $myCreatures[0].name != "Golem") {
		return $AIHand.indexOf('Prison')
	};

	if ($gregTools.includesCreature($myCreatures,$golem)) {
		if ($AIHand.indexOf('Shatter') > -1) {
			if ($AICreatures[0] && $AICreatures[0].name == 'undeadInai') {return -1}
			else {return $AIHand.indexOf('Shatter')}
		}
	};
	
	
	if ($AICreatures[0] && $AICreatures[0].name.indexOf('prison')==0 && $AIHand.indexOf('crackPrison') > -1) {
		return $AIHand.indexOf('crackPrison')
	};
	return -1;
},
summon: function(what){
	what.location = $AIHomeBase;
	$AICreatures.push(what);
	this.forget(what.name);
},
forget: function(whatString){
	if ($AIHand.indexOf(whatString) > -1) {
		$AIHand.splice($AIHand.indexOf(whatString),1)
	};
},
}>>

passages.name: You had your justifications.
passages.text:
<<print "\s"You did not save them\s", she says. \s"My people. Not even one.\s"
\sn\sn
And it's true. You had your memory, your champion in her shining moment. And when she fell, there was nothing more to see. But wasn't that the point, after all? To abstract away each suffering particular, to be as ruthless, as relentlessly pragmatic as possible?
\sn\sn
\s"Not a game\s", she says. \s"Not any more.\s"
\sn\sn
But she's wrong. You know exactly [[what to do.|what to do redux]]">>
